You're right - there's an issue where both `onCreate()` and `onResume()` are triggering API calls before the first one completes. This happens because during activity startup, `onCreate()` immediately flows into `onResume()`, and if your API call initiated in `onCreate()` hasn't completed yet, `onResume()` will trigger another one.

## Solution Using a Loading Flag in ViewModel:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/presentation/screens/dashboard/ActivityContent/MainViewModel.kt
class MainViewModel @Inject constructor(
 // your existing dependencies...
) : ViewModel() {

 // Add a flag to track if a request is in progress
 private val _isLoading = MutableStateFlow(false)
 val isLoading: StateFlow<Boolean> = _isLoading.asStateFlow()

 // Existing userValues Flow
 private val _userValues = MutableStateFlow<Resource<LeetCodeUserInfo>>(Resource.Loading())
 val userValues: StateFlow<Resource<LeetCodeUserInfo>> = _userValues.asStateFlow()

 fun loadUserDetails() {
 // Check if a load is already in progress
 if (_isLoading.value) {
 return // Skip this request, one is already running
 }

 viewModelScope.launch {
 _isLoading.value = true

 // Your existing loading logic
 getUserInfoUseCase(username = username, forceRefresh = false)
 .collect {
 _userValues.value = it

 // Set loading to false when we get a terminal state
 if (it is Resource.Success || it is Resource.Error) {
 _isLoading.value = false
 }
 }
 }
 }

 fun reloadUserDetails() {
 // Same check to avoid duplicate calls
 if (_isLoading.value) {
 return
 }

 viewModelScope.launch {
 _isLoading.value = true

 // Your existing reload logic, but with forceRefresh = true if needed
 getUserInfoUseCase(username = username, forceRefresh = true)
 .collect {
 _userValues.value = it

 if (it is Resource.Success || it is Resource.Error) {
 _isLoading.value = false
 }
 }
 }
 }
}
```

## Updated MainActivity:

```kotlin:app/src/main/java/com/devrachit/ken/presentation/screens/dashboard/ActivityContent/MainActivity.kt
@AndroidEntryPoint
class MainActivity : ComponentActivity() {

 val viewModel: MainViewModel by viewModels()

 override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
 super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
 setupWindow()
 val username = intent.getStringExtra(NAVKEYUSERNAME) ?: "Guest_User"

 // Load user details in onCreate
 viewModel.loadUserDetails()

 setContent {
 val uiStates = viewModel.userValues.collectAsStateWithLifecycle().value
 DashboardContent(username=username,uiState= uiStates)
 }
 }

 override fun onResume() {
 super.onResume()
 // Call reloadUserDetails which contains the loading check
 viewModel.reloadUserDetails()
 }

 // Rest of your activity code...
}
```

## Why This Works:

1. The `_isLoading` flag tracks when an API call is in progress
2. Both `loadUserDetails()` and `reloadUserDetails()` check this flag before making a request
3. If a request is already in progress, subsequent calls will be ignored
4. The flag is only reset when we receive a terminal state (Success or Error)

This approach ensures that even if `onCreate()` immediately flows into `onResume()` before the API call completes, the second call in `onResume()` will see that a request is already in progress and skip its operation.

The solution leverages the structured concurrency of coroutines and doesn't require any additional state management or lifecycle tracking."},{"role":"user","content":"<user_query>
